{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492479"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:32:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:32:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1075"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1075"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.14,0.31,0.13,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1075"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111842"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1075"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1075"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93912"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41131"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44766"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111842"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of unexplained 7kg weight loss and mid-epigastric pain radiating to the back. He had a basal cell carcinoma completely excised from his nose 2 years prior, was recently diagnosed with diabetes despite a BMI of 22 kg/m\u00b2, and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe works as an accountant and smokes 10 cigarettes per day. He consumes two standard drinks of alcohol per night. As the patient was adopted as a child, he is unsure about any significant family history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild epigastric tenderness without a palpable mass. Investigations reveal a two cm diameter mass in the head of the pancreas on computed tomography.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the risk factor most associated with this patients likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Smoking","BRCA1 gene carrier","Heavy alcohol consumption","Personal history of skin cancer","Familial atypical multiple mole syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPancreatic cancer has several established risk factors, with genetic syndromes being among the strongest. \u003Cstrong\u003EFamilial atypical multiple mole syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (FAMM), also known as dysplastic nevus syndrome, is associated with mutations in the CDKN2A (p16) gene and confers a 30-70 fold increased risk of pancreatic cancer. This syndrome is characterized by multiple atypical nevi and a strong family history of melanoma. It represents one of the highest risk factors for pancreatic cancer among all genetic syndromes. Patients should be referred to a genetic specialist for management of their cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmoking\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant modifiable risk factor for pancreatic cancer, increasing risk by 2-3 times compared to non-smokers. It is estimated to be responsible for approximately 20-25% of all pancreatic cancer cases. The risk increases with both duration and intensity of smoking, and decreases gradually after smoking cessation, though it may take up to 20 years to return to baseline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA1 gene carrier\u003C/strong\u003E status is primarily associated with increased risk of breast and ovarian cancers. While BRCA1 mutations do increase pancreatic cancer risk, the magnitude is modest (approximately 2-3 fold) compared to FAMM syndrome. BRCA2 mutations actually confer a higher pancreatic cancer risk (5-10 fold) than BRCA1 mutations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeavy alcohol consumption\u003C/strong\u003E (\u0026gt;4 standard drinks/day) may increase pancreatic cancer risk, but the association is weaker than for smoking or genetic syndromes. The mechanism is thought to be related to alcohol\u0027s role in promoting chronic pancreatitis, which is itself a risk factor. Moderate alcohol consumption has not been consistently linked to increased risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersonal history of skin cancer\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly non-melanoma skin cancers like basal cell or squamous cell carcinoma, has not been strongly associated with pancreatic cancer risk. However, a history of melanoma may be associated with increased risk, particularly if related to FAMM syndrome or other genetic predispositions that affect both melanoma and pancreatic cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EModifiable risk factors include increased body mass index, heavy alcohol use, smoking and long-standing diabetes. Whilst symptoms are subtle, it has the highest mortality rate of all main types of cancer so should have a high suspicion for patients presenting with vague abdominal or back pain especially with weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Familial atypical multiple mole syndrome (FAMM) is associated with a 30-70 fold increased risk of pancreatic cancer.","Smoking is the most significant modifiable risk factor for pancreatic cancer, increasing risk by 2-3 times.","BRCA1 gene mutations are primarily associated with breast and ovarian cancer risk, with a modest 2-3 fold increased risk for pancreatic cancer."],"references":["Ducreux M, Cuhna A, Caramella C, Hollebecque A, Burtin P, Go\u00e9r\u00e9 D, et al. Cancer of the pancreas: ESMO Clinical Practice Guidelines for diagnosis, treatment and follow-up. Annals of Oncology. 2015. Available from: https://www.annalsofoncology.org/article/S0923-7534(19)47178-0/fulltext#secst0075","Park W, Chawla A, O\u0027Reilly EM. Pancreatic Cancer A Review. JAMA 2021; 326:851-62.","Garajova, I, Peroni M, Gelsomino F, et al. A Simple Overview of Pancreatic Cancer Treatment for Clinical Oncologists. Curr. Oncol. 2023; 30: 9587\u20139601.","Loveday B, Lipton L, Thomason B. Pancreatic cancer: An update on diagnosis and management. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2019: 48 (12).  Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/december/pancreatic-cancer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93912"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1075"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93912"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T13:59:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T14:00:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1075"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111842"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":